2019 vs 2020 CitiBike

AnaPatricia Olvera

7/23/2020

The purpose of this is to compare 2019 vs 2020 data from the CitiBike in NYC.

marchJune19 <- rbind(read.csv("citibikeData/RealData/201903-citibike-tripdata.csv"),
                     read.csv("citibikeData/RealData/201904-citibike-tripdata.csv"),
                     read.csv("citibikeData/RealData/201905-citibike-tripdata.csv"),
                     read.csv("citibikeData/RealData/201906-citibike-tripdata.csv"))
marchJune20 <- rbind(read.csv("citibikeData/202003-citibike-tripdata.csv"),
                     read.csv("citibikeData/202004-citibike-tripdata.csv"),
                     read.csv("citibikeData/202005-citibike-tripdata.csv"),
                     read.csv("citibikeData/202006-citibike-tripdata.csv"))

First, let’s clean both data sets

marchJune19 <- marchJune19%>%na.omit()
marchJune19 <- marchJune19%>%filter( tripduration >=0 & tripduration <= 1800)
marchJune19 <- marchJune19%>%filter( (2019 - birth.year ) <= 70)
marchJune20 <- marchJune20%>%na.omit()
marchJune20 <- marchJune20%>%filter( tripduration >=0 & tripduration <= 1800)
marchJune20 <- marchJune20%>%filter( (2019 - birth.year ) <= 70)

Now let’s create a weekday column

marchJune19 <- marchJune19%>%separate(starttime, c("start.date", "start.time"), " ")
marchJune19 <- marchJune19%>%separate(stoptime, c("stop.date", "stop.time"), " ")
marchJune19$weekday <- weekdays(as.Date(marchJune19$start.date))
marchJune20 <- marchJune20%>%separate(starttime, c("start.date", "start.time"), " ")
marchJune20 <- marchJune20%>%separate(stoptime, c("stop.date", "stop.time"), " ")
marchJune20$weekday <- weekdays(as.Date(marchJune20$start.date))
g <- function(y){
  if( y == 1){
    return("Male")
  }
  if( y== 2){
    return("Female")
  }
  if(y==0){
    return("Unknown")
  }
}

Let’s divide the user types for gender, and generations:

marchJune19$gender<- sapply(marchJune19$gender, g)
marchJune20$gender<- sapply(marchJune20$gender, g)

Average trip duration: 2019:

mean( marchJune19$tripduration, trim = 0, na.rm = T) / 60
## [1] 11.3472

2020:

mean( marchJune20$tripduration, trim = 0, na.rm = T) / 60
## [1] 13.57526

Most popular start stations in 2019:

colBar3 <- brewer.pal(10, "Set3")
with(diamonds, barplot(rev(sort(table(marchJune19$start.station.name), decreasing = T )[1:10]), width = 10, main= "Top Start stations", space= 1, xlab = "Stations", legend.text = T, col= colBar3, names.arg = F, args.legend= list(x = "topleft", bty = "n", cex= 0.45)))

Perishing Square Noth was the top 1 station, reporting a bit more than 50,000 trips starting from this point.

Most popular start stations in 2020:

with(diamonds, barplot(rev(sort(table(marchJune20$start.station.name), decreasing = T )[1:10]), width = 10, main= "Top Start stations", space= 1, xlab = "Stations", legend.text = T, col= colBar3, names.arg = F, args.legend= list(x = "topleft", bty = "n", cex= 0.40)))

1Ave & E 68St is the top one start station repoting a bit more than 20,000 trips starting there.

Most popular end station in 2019:

colBar2 <- brewer.pal(10, "Paired") 
with(diamonds, barplot(rev(sort(table(marchJune19$end.station.name), decreasing = T)[1:10]), width = 10,  main= "Top End stations", space= 1, xlab = "Stations", legend.text = T, col= colBar2, names.arg = F, args.legend= list(x = "topleft", bty = "n", cex= 0.45)))

Pershing Square North is the most popular end station, with about 50,000 trips ended here. Most popular end station 2020:

with(diamonds, barplot(rev(sort(table(marchJune20$end.station.name), decreasing = T)[1:10]), width = 10,  main= "Top End stations", space= 1, xlab = "Stations", legend.text = T, col= colBar2, names.arg = F, args.legend= list(x = "topleft", bty = "n", cex= 0.40)))

Again, 1 Ave & E 68St is the most popular end station.

Busiest day of the week in 2019:

with(diamonds, barplot(rev(sort(table(marchJune19$weekday) )[1:7]), width = 10, main= "Busiest Day of the Week", xlab= "Day of the Week"))

The busiest day of the week in 2019 was Wednesday. Busiest day of the week in 2020:

with(diamonds, barplot(rev(sort(table(marchJune20$weekday) )[1:7]), width = 10, main= "Busiest Day of the Week", xlab= "Day of the Week"))

The busiest day of the week in 2020 is Sunday.

Who biked more in the busiest day in 2019?

ggplot(marchJune19, aes(x= weekday, fill= gender)) + geom_bar( stat = "count" , na.rm= T, 
                                                              position = position_dodge(width = 0.25)) +
  labs(title= "Who bikes more in the week?", x= "Week day", y= "")

Males biked more. Who biked more in the busiest day in 2020?

ggplot(marchJune20, aes(x= weekday, fill= gender)) + geom_bar( stat = "count" , na.rm= T, 
                                                              position = position_dodge(width = 0.25)) +
  labs(title= "Who bikes more in the week?", x= "Week day", y= "")

Again, males biked more.

let’s compare month by month the change

the Start Date is divided by year, month, and day

marchJune19 <- marchJune19%>% separate(start.date, c("year", "month", "day"), "-")
marchJune20 <- marchJune20%>% separate(start.date, c("year", "month", "day"), "-")

now we will separate the data into different data frames

march19 <- filter(marchJune19, month == '03')
march20 <- filter(marchJune20, month == '03')

april19 <- filter(marchJune19, month == '04')
april20 <- filter(marchJune20, month == '04')

may19 <- filter(marchJune19, month == '05')
may20 <- filter(marchJune20, month == '05')

june19 <- filter(marchJune19, month == '06')
june20 <- filter(marchJune20, month == '06')

now let’s plot!! 2019 will be green 2020 will be blue

ggplot() + 
geom_point(data=march19 , aes(x=march19$day), color='green', stat = "count", na.rm= T) + 
geom_point(data= march20, aes(x=march20$day), color='blue', stat = "count", na.rm= T) + labs( title = "March 2019 vs March 2020", x= "Date") 
## Warning: Use of `march19$day` is discouraged. Use `day` instead.
## Warning: Use of `march20$day` is discouraged. Use `day` instead.

ggplot()+
  geom_point(data = april19, aes(x=april19$day), color= 'green', stat = "count", na.rm = T)+
  geom_point(data = april20, aes(x=april20$day), color= 'blue', stat = "count", na.rm = T)+
  labs(title= "April 2019 vs April 2020", x= "Date")
## Warning: Use of `april19$day` is discouraged. Use `day` instead.
## Warning: Use of `april20$day` is discouraged. Use `day` instead.

ggplot()+
  geom_point(data = may19, aes(x=may19$day), color= 'green', stat = "count", na.rm = T)+
  geom_point(data = may20, aes(x=may20$day), color= 'blue', stat = "count", na.rm = T)+
  labs(title= "May 2019 vs May 2020", x= "Date")
## Warning: Use of `may19$day` is discouraged. Use `day` instead.

ggplot()+

  geom_line()+
  geom_point(data = june20, aes(x=june20$day), color= 'red', stat = "count", na.rm = T)+
  geom_line()+
  labs(title= "June 2019 vs June 2020", x= "Date")
